<section>
    <h2>Description</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;ins&gt;</code> element indicates text that has been added to a document. It is the counterpart to <a href="/docs/elements/native/del/"><code>&lt;del&gt;</code></a> and the two are commonly used together to show document revisions. VB removes the browser default underline and replaces it with a subtle green background tint and a solid green bottom border, keeping insertions visually distinct from <a href="/docs/elements/native/u/"><code>&lt;u&gt;</code></a> annotations and <a href="/docs/elements/native/mark/"><code>&lt;mark&gt;</code></a> highlights.</p>
    <p>Like <code>&lt;del&gt;</code>, it supports <code>cite</code> and <code>datetime</code> attributes for machine-readable context about the insertion.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>When to Use</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Document revisions:</strong> Track additions in legal documents, contracts, or policies</li>
      <li><strong>Edit history:</strong> Show what was added in collaborative documents</li>
      <li><strong>Diff displays:</strong> Show added code or text in version comparisons</li>
      <li><strong>Corrections:</strong> Indicate new information that replaces deleted content</li>
      <li><strong>Track changes:</strong> Similar to "track changes" in word processors</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>When NOT to Use</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Visual underline only:</strong> Use <a href="/docs/elements/native/u/"><code>&lt;u&gt;</code></a> or CSS for purely decorative underlines</li>
      <li><strong>New content without revision context:</strong> Only use when tracking changes matters</li>
      <li><strong>Relevance highlighting:</strong> Use <a href="/docs/elements/native/mark/"><code>&lt;mark&gt;</code></a> for drawing attention without editorial semantics</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Examples</h2>

    <browser-window src="/docs/snippets/demos/del-ins-examples.html" url="del-ins-examples.html" title="del and ins examples" shadow></browser-window>

